"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:10.5.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">10.5.2</span> Bracelet, armlet, anklet</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אֶצְעָדָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’ets‘adah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num31:50\">NUM 31:50</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam1:10\">2SA 1:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">עֶכֶס</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(‘ekes)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa3:18\">ISA 3:18</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צָמִיד</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsamid)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:22\">GEN 24:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:30\">GEN 24:30</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:47\">GEN 24:47</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num31:50\">NUM 31:50</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:11\">EZK 16:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek23:42\">EZK 23:42</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צְעָדָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(ts‘adah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa3:20\">ISA 3:20</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">χλιδών</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chlidōn)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt10:4\">JDT 10:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir21:21\">SIR 21:21</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ψέλιον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(pselion)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt10:4\">JDT 10:4</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0532_bracelets_gold.jpg\" alt=\"Bracelets with antelope-head ends\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Bracelets with antelope-head ends (Walters Art Museum, Public domain, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The bracelet/armlet was a piece of jewelry worn on the wrist/arm. It was round and made of metal.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The bracelet was worn on the wrist while the armlet was pushed up the arm, usually above the elbow. Where a distinction must be made between one part of the arm and another, the Hebrew word <em>tsamid</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:11\">EZK 16:11</a> may be translated “bracelets on your wrists.”</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num31:50\">NUM 31:50</a>: Where different words do not exist for a ring worn on the wrist and a ring worn on the upper arm, it is possible to use an inclusive term in this verse; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> has “jewelry” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>).</p>\n<p>Translators must be careful not to use a word that indicates an object worn on the arm but that is made of something other than metal. For example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> has “arm-band” in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam1:10\">2SA 1:10</a>, but this could be misunderstood in modern English to mean an insignia made of cloth or plastic.</p>\n<p>For the Hebrew words <em>‘ekes</em> and <em>ts‘adah</em>, see the discussion on <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa3:18-Isa3:23\">ISA 3:18–ISA 3:23</a> at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">10.5 Jewelry, ornaments&lt;REALIA:10.5&gt;</a>.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt10:4\">JDT 10:4</a> the two Greek words <em>chlidōn</em> and <em>pselion</em> can both mean “bracelet“ (for the arm) and “anklet” (for the leg). Where two distinct words exist, they can both be used. It is also possible to say something like “decorative metal bands for the wrist and the ankle.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
